		"author": "Shari Y. Manning"
	},
	{
		"quote": "The explanation of what creates BPD that you just read is called the biosocial theory of borderline personality disorder: your loved one came by this problem by virtue of innate emotional traits plus an environment that, intentionally or unintentionally, invalidated his or her childhood emotional experience.",
		"title": "Loving Someone with Borderline Personality Disorder: How to Keep Out-of-Control Emotions from Destroying Your Relationship",
		"author": "Shari Y. Manning"
	},
	{
		"quote": "Learn to ask what the other person needs by asking whenever a friend confides in you.",
		"title": "Loving Someone with Borderline Personality Disorder: How to Keep Out-of-Control Emotions from Destroying Your Relationship",
		"author": "Shari Y. Manning"
	},
	{
		"quote": "Anger cannot be maintained in the face of compassion.",
		"title": "Loving Someone with Borderline Personality Disorder: How to Keep Out-of-Control Emotions from Destroying Your Relationship",
		"author": "Shari Y. Manning"
	},
	{
		"quote": "Whenever emotion begins to build, stop and validate again.",
		"title": "Loving Someone with Borderline Personality Disorder: How to Keep Out-of-Control Emotions from Destroying Your Relationship",
		"author": "Shari Y. Manning"
	},
	{
		"quote": "Don’t correct or contradict your loved one in an attempt to reassure: Say “I know you feel like you’re stupid.” (Don’t go on to say “But you’re not.”)",
		"title": "Loving Someone with Borderline Personality Disorder: How to Keep Out-of-Control Emotions from Destroying Your Relationship",
		"author": "Shari Y. Manning"
	},
	{
		"quote": "you pay attention to and label your experience, your emotion immediately begins to regulate. But",
		"title": "Loving Someone with Borderline Personality Disorder: How to Keep Out-of-Control Emotions from Destroying Your Relationship",
		"author": "Shari Y. Manning"
	},
	{
		"quote": "Think of yourself as a coach. Your loved one is still the athlete and could compete without you, but things will go much better if you are on the sidelines.",
		"title": "Loving Someone with Borderline Personality Disorder: How to Keep Out-of-Control Emotions from Destroying Your Relationship",
		"author": "Shari Y. Manning"
	},
	{
		"quote": "people with BPD are naturally emotional and have learned to distrust and discount their emotions.",
		"title": "Loving Someone with Borderline Personality Disorder: How to Keep Out-of-Control Emotions from Destroying Your Relationship",
		"author": "Shari Y. Manning"
	},
	{
		"quote": "To someone with BPD, any response that doesn’t validate his experience of pain is unsympathetic. So trying to help him solve the problem is validating only if you acknowledged how much pain the problem is causing. Trying to downplay the magnitude of the problem, on the other hand, is invalidating of how much pain the problem is causing your loved one. Trying to reassure him that he can solve the problem is invalidating of the shame or guilt he feels at not having been able to do so thus far.",
		"title": "Loving Someone with Borderline Personality Disorder: How to Keep Out-of-Control Emotions from Destroying Your Relationship",
		"author": "Shari Y. Manning"
	},
	{
		"quote": "A general rule is to make at least two validating statements (“I understand”; “This is really important to you”) before trying to solve the problem.",
		"title": "Loving Someone with Borderline Personality Disorder: How to Keep Out-of-Control Emotions from Destroying Your Relationship",
		"author": "Shari Y. Manning"
	},
	{
		"quote": "whenever a person with BPD answers the question “How can I help?” with something like “You can’t help; there’s nothing anyone can do,” you should go back to validation. Say, “I know it feels that way right now. I don’t know if I can help. I am sure willing to try.”",
		"title": "Loving Someone with Borderline Personality Disorder: How to Keep Out-of-Control Emotions from Destroying Your Relationship",
		"author": "Shari Y. Manning"
	},
	{
		"quote": "Finally, people with BPD are often overly perfectionistic.",
		"title": "Loving Someone with Borderline Personality Disorder: How to Keep Out-of-Control Emotions from Destroying Your Relationship",
		"author": "Shari Y. Manning"
	},
	{
		"quote": "She has to talk about whatever it is over and over while making eye contact to get the shame to go down.",
		"title": "Loving Someone with Borderline Personality Disorder: How to Keep Out-of-Control Emotions from Destroying Your Relationship",
		"author": "Shari Y. Manning"
	},
	{
		"quote": "Don’t reinforce shame. Don’t communicate that she should feel shame (don’t say, “Wow, that really was a stupid response”).",
		"title": "Loving Someone with Borderline Personality Disorder: How to Keep Out-of-Control Emotions from Destroying Your Relationship",
		"author": "Shari Y. Manning"
	},
	{
		"quote": "shame is often what is driving your loved one to act helpless.",
		"title": "Loving Someone with Borderline Personality Disorder: How to Keep Out-of-Control Emotions from Destroying Your Relationship",
		"author": "Shari Y. Manning"
	},
	{
		"quote": "often what you will see is your loved one alternating between extreme emotional arousal (crying, etc.) and extreme emotional avoidance (no expression at all).",
		"title": "Loving Someone with Borderline Personality Disorder: How to Keep Out-of-Control Emotions from Destroying Your Relationship",
		"author": "Shari Y. Manning"
	},
	{
		"quote": "impulsive behavior is often one sign that a person is attempting to shut down emotions. Another way to recognize inhibited grieving is through lack of facial expression or body language that you would expect with that emotion.",
		"title": "Loving Someone with Borderline Personality Disorder: How to Keep Out-of-Control Emotions from Destroying Your Relationship",
		"author": "Shari Y. Manning"
	},
	{
		"quote": "When people go out and get drunk so that they don’t have to go home and be alone with an emotion, they are intentionally avoiding or inhibiting emotion.",
		"title": "Loving Someone with Borderline Personality Disorder: How to Keep Out-of-Control Emotions from Destroying Your Relationship",
		"author": "Shari Y. Manning"
	},
	{
