		"author": "Jon Krakauer"
	},
	{
		"quote": "Moreover, Lisak said, self-blame seems “to be more accentuated” when victims are raped by an acquaintance. He said that non-stranger rape is “oftentimes more difficult to recover from,” as well, because “if you have been assaulted by somebody you thought you could trust, how do you restore your sense of trust in the world or in people? And how do you trust yourself?” After being betrayed and violated by a person you were sure would never harm you, “how do you then trust your own judgment thereafter?…That’s a hard thing to resolve. And it seems to feed self-blame….You say, ‘Well, it was my fault it happened, so I’ll fix the things that I did wrong, and that will prevent this from happening to me again.”",
