	{
		"quote": "As the DOJ report pointed out, the successful prosecution of rape cases—particularly cases involving non-stranger rape—requires a sophisticated grasp of the latest legal and scientific knowledge. “It is imperative,” the report admonished, “for state and local prosecutors to be aware of rape myths and how juries may be influenced by these myths.” Prosecutors needed to understand the neurochemical basis for the counterintuitive behavior that victims often display during sexual assaults, and in their aftermath. They had to be able to explain to juries why rape victims don’t always respond in a manner that conforms to jurors’ expectations, as well as why victims may not be able to recall the details of being raped. Prior to the initiation of the DOJ investigation, the report noted, “the County Attorney’s Office provided little, if any, such training.”",
